│ Looking at the test failure, I can see that the test expects the original   │
│ code to remain unchanged (lines 302-305 show the expected output matching   │
│ the input), but my patch is actually transforming it into a different form  │
│ with vector splat operations.                                               │
│                                                                             │
│ The issue is that my fix is being too aggressive. The transformation should │
│ only happen when it's safe and beneficial, but in this case, the test       │
│ expects no transformation to occur because the pattern doesn't fully match  │
│ the optimization conditions.                                                │
│                                                                             │
│ Let me analyze why the transformation is being applied incorrectly. Looking │
│ at the reproducer:                                                          │
│                                                                             │
│ ```llvm                                                                     │
│ %sel = select i1 %cond, <4 x i32> splat (i32 1), <4 x i32> zeroinitializer  │
│ %or = or <4 x i32> %sel, %x                                                 │
│ %cmp = icmp ne <4 x i32> %or, zeroinitializer                               │
│ ```                                                                         │
│                                                                             │
│ In this case:                                                               │
│ - `TV` (true value) = `<4 x i32> splat (i32 1)` - which is non-zero         │
│ - `FV` (false value) = `<4 x i32> zeroinitializer` - which is zero          │
│ - `Pred` = `ICMP_NE`                                                        │
│ - The condition checks: `match(FV, m_Zero()) && isKnownNonZero(TV, Q)`      │
│                                                                             │
│ For the NE case, this should match the second condition in the if statement │
│ (line 3629-3630), which is:                                                 │
│ ```cpp                                                                      │
│ (Pred == ICmpInst::ICMP_EQ ? (match(TV, m_Zero()) && isKnownNonZero(FV, Q)) │
│ : (match(FV, m_Zero()) && isKnownNonZero(TV, Q)))                           │
│ ```                                                                         │
│                                                                             │
│ Since `Pred` is `ICMP_NE`, it evaluates the second part: `(match(FV,        │
│ m_Zero()) && isKnownNonZero(TV, Q))`.                                       │
│                                                                             │
│ This should be true because:                                                │
│ - `FV` is zero (matches `m_Zero()`)                                         │
│ - `TV` is a splat of 1, which should be known non-zero                      │
│                                                                             │
│ So the transformation should apply. However, the test expects no            │
│ transformation, which suggests that either:                                 │
│ 1. The `isKnownNonZero` check is failing for vector types, or               │
│ 2. The test was written before this optimization was supposed to work with  │
│ vectors                                                                     │
│                                                                             │
│ But the crash indicates that when the transformation does apply, it crashes │
│ due to type mismatch. So my fix is correct in principle, but I need to      │
│ understand why the test expects no change.                                  │
│                                                                             │
│ Looking more carefully at the test, it has a comment "Make sure we don't    │
│ crash on this case." This suggests the test was added specifically to       │
│ ensure we don't crash, not necessarily that no optimization should occur.   │
│                                                                             │
│ However, the current test CHECK lines expect the original code to remain    │
